ormly conclude that a well-informed and motivated citizenry is the most powerful force for creating the political will necessary to effect change at the national level. In addition to a critical evaluation of the current state of human rights protection in each of these African nations, the contributors outline existing national resources available for protecting human rights and provide recommendations for more effective and practical use of these resources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHuman rightszAfrica. 0aRule of lawzAfrica. 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAsian Studies.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aMiddle Eastern Studies.  aPolitical Science.1 aAn-Na'im, Abdullahi Ahmed, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAn-Na\x27im, Abdullahi Ahmed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshenafi, Meaza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAwori, Taaka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusia, Nana K. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGahamanyi, Bibiane Mbaye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHussein, Siddig A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKane, lbrahima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMondlane, Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNouaydi, Abdelaziz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aObiagwu, Chinonye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOdinkalu, Chidi Anselm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeafield, Lucrecia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc